    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1260933931" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1260933931" />
    <a title="Purabi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12945402-purabi"><img alt="Purabi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618407415p2/12945402.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1260933931?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Purabi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Purabi" href="/user/show/12945402-purabi">Purabi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780393337105" href="/book/show/7283424-jacob-s-ladder">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1260933931" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8997167972167544141">It is a military novel describing in great detail military strategies used by the Confederates under General Lee and we get to witness the savagery in Virginia’s Wilderness Campaign in 1864. Donald McCaig has done a very good job of describing in detail horrors of the civil war that tore through America pitting men against men, men against their former slaves. The book has love, passion, cruelty, racism, violence. It’s an eye-opener to the facts of life lived in the era of huge plantations where</span>
  <span id="freeText8997167972167544141" style="display:none">It is a military novel describing in great detail military strategies used by the Confederates under General Lee and we get to witness the savagery in Virginia’s Wilderness Campaign in 1864. Donald McCaig has done a very good job of describing in detail horrors of the civil war that tore through America pitting men against men, men against their former slaves. The book has love, passion, cruelty, racism, violence. It’s an eye-opener to the facts of life lived in the era of huge plantations where slaves worked from morning until night with their masters and mistresses benefitting from their hard work. The Confederate soldiers, mostly landowners and never having worked harder than laying the bullwhip on a slaves back for some alleged misdeed, would be required to fight for life and country. We see the slave Midge or Maggie, a mulatto, sold along with her baby son Jacob, simply because Duncan Gatewood heir to the Gatewood Plantation is the father and, of course, the family should not bear any taint of this connection. Scandal had to be stemmed at all costs. The author mentions this child time and time again and yet we never get to see his growing years or accomplishments except for a chance remark by family at the end of the book. Understandably this is a civil war saga but I would have loved to have followed the growing years of Jacob especially since the quotation from Genesis 28:10-15 in the front of the book sets the stage. All in all, it is a great book, forthright, compassionate and detailed, teaching those of us who do not know too much about the American Civil war the complex issues faced, not least of which was the displacement of slaves under their newly found freedom. A freedom great in concept but not so in reality when even the Union soldiers could not or would not afford equality to those that were former slaves. It was surprising to discover once the war ended with Lincoln’s Union soldiers defeating the Confederates, some of the freed slaves yearned for their old way of life. For even freedom, when it finally arrived, did not bring them dignity or a sense of identity. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8997167972167544141" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

